# 22_dialog_rebuild_pilot — substrate-layer test for the
# ThemeEditDialog OK button.
#
# History: this script was the s199 m1 pilot for the heap-allocated
# dialog-rebuild pattern. s200 m1 converted ThemeEditDialog to a
# hide-on-close singleton owned by MainWindow; the substrate widget
# now lives for the app's lifetime instead of being torn down on
# every close. The script asserts the same surface (label query +
# click verb) — what's changed is what the surface *proves*.
#
# Before (s199 m1): proves force_unregister_subtree synchronously
# removes substrate widgets from the registry so the next heap-
# allocated open doesn't crash on a duplicate name.
#
# After (s200 m1): proves the singleton's substrate widget
# constructs lazily on first show() and stays registered for the
# app's lifetime, so subsequent opens find the already-registered
# widget without reconstructing.
#
# In both shapes the script runs the same lines; what differs is
# the architectural meaning of the two-open protocol.
#
# Modality: non-modal (set in the ctor). Lets the Scripter keep
# focus while the dialog is open.
#
# Test protocol — REQUIRES TWO MANUAL DIALOG OPENS:
#
# This script can't open the dialog itself. The Edit-theme button
# on ThemesPanel is the only path to ThemeEditDialog, and
# ThemesPanel isn't substrate-migrated yet (blocked on the
# dynamic-widget naming question — see LEDGER "Open questions").
# Manual opens are bracketed by script runs that drive the
# substrate-side behaviour.
#
#   1. Open Curvz with a fresh / default document and project.
#   2. Open the Scripter window.
#   3. Load this script.
#   4. **Manually**: in the Themes panel (inspector sidebar), click
#      the Edit icon on any theme row. ThemeEditDialog opens for
#      the first time — build() runs, the widget tree constructs,
#      dlg_te_ok registers in the substrate.
#   5. Switch back to the Scripter and run the script. The script:
#        - asserts dlg_te_ok label == "OK"
#        - dlg_te_ok click → on_ok fires, commits, hides the window.
#      In the singleton form the widget stays in the registry after
#      the close; hide-on-close just hides.
#   6. **Manually**: click the Edit icon again to reopen the Theme
#      Editor. show() now runs sync_from_working() against the
#      already-built widget tree (m_built==true). dlg_te_ok is the
#      same Scriptable as in step 5; no re-registration happens.
#   7. Run the script a second time. Should produce identical PASS
#      results — proves the substrate widget survives close/hide
#      cycles and stays addressable.
#
# If both runs PASS and Curvz doesn't crash between steps 5 and 6,
# the singleton conversion is green. The pre-s200 force_unregister
# discipline is no longer load-bearing for this dialog (the utility
# stays in curvz::utils for PropertiesPanel's inspector-rebuild
# site, which is unrelated).
#
# DSL note: Button substrate exposes `click` (invoke) and `label`
# (query). The label is a String — quote literals.

#[sub] Dialog OK button — resolves and has the expected label.

assert dlg_te_ok label == "OK"

#[sub] Dialog OK button — click commits and hides the dialog.
#[sub] In the singleton form, hide-on-close keeps the substrate
#[sub] widget alive; subsequent opens find it already registered.

dlg_te_ok click

#[sub] Done. Run this script once per Theme Editor open. If both
#[sub] runs PASS and Curvz didn't crash between manual opens, the
#[sub] singleton form is doing its job.
